overview_summary: The adjacent landowners consist largely of private LLCs formed for land investment or development, alongside the county government and a major utility. Bianco 20 LLC and Sonoran Land Fund LLC are speculative landholders positioning their parcels for future projects or resale, rather than long-term local stewards. A joint venture (Ethington & Hwy 84 LLC) backed by an experienced land brokerage (Willis family) and outside investors suggests plans for commercial/industrial development on its site. Pinal County (local government) and Arizona Public Service (state’s largest electric utility) are heavyweight stakeholders generally inclined to facilitate growth and infrastructure, though each will act to ensure their public and operational interests are protected.

neighbors.name: Bianco 20 LLC
neighbors.claims: Bianco 20 LLC owns approximately 21.76 acres of undeveloped land near Bianco Road in Casa Grande, Pinal County ([www.kallhoffteam.com](https://www.kallhoffteam.com/property/22-6876448-0-n-bianco-road-casa-grande-AZ-85194#:~:text=Lot%20Size%20Acres%20%20,7411)). The property is listed for sale as a heavy industrial site, with preliminary site plans and engineering included to attract development interest ([www.kallhoffteam.com](https://www.kallhoffteam.com/property/22-6876448-0-n-bianco-road-casa-grande-AZ-85194#:~:text=County%20%20,Casa%20Grande%20Elementary%20District)). The LLC’s ownership is not openly disclosed in state records (members are not listed), so its beneficial owner remains unknown. No public history of community engagement or political activity is associated with this entity (it appears to be a passive land investment vehicle).
neighbors.influence_justification: Small landholder with no known local profile or political ties; primarily a speculative seller of one parcel.

approach_recommendations.engage: Identify and approach the LLC’s managing agent or representative (through the listing broker) with a purchase or partnership offer; emphasize quick ROI to align with their sell-side interests

neighbors.name: Sonoran Land Fund LLC
neighbors.claims: Sonoran Land Fund, LLC is a Delaware-formed investment company (established October 2012) registered to do business in Arizona ([www.bizprofile.net](https://www.bizprofile.net/az/phoenix/sonoran-land-fund-llc#:~:text=Reason%20for%20Status%20%20,Perpetual)). Its managing member is Compound Holdings LLC of Phoenix, indicating the fund is controlled by a Phoenix-based investment group ([www.bizprofile.net](https://www.bizprofile.net/az/phoenix/sonoran-land-fund-llc#:~:text=Overseeing%20the%20operations%20and%20compliance,holding%20the%20position%20of%20Member)). The fund has assembled a large number of adjacent parcels in the area (over 20 parcels spanning a substantial acreage), presumably banking the land for future development or value appreciation (no active operations on the land). The LLC’s filings do not reveal individual owners or officers beyond the corporate member, so the ultimate beneficiary ownership is not publicly known ([www.bizprofile.net](https://www.bizprofile.net/az/phoenix/sonoran-land-fund-llc#:~:text=Overseeing%20the%20operations%20and%20compliance,holding%20the%20position%20of%20Member)). There are no reported civic activities or local alliances involving this entity; its behavior aligns with land speculation for profit rather than community engagement.
neighbors.influence_justification: Outside investor with significant land holdings but no local employment or public role; influence limited to property rights and capital for potential opposition

approach_recommendations.engage: Reach out via Compound Holdings (Phoenix) to discuss mutually beneficial timing or land swaps; ensure the project doesn’t hinder their parcel values to avoid conflict

neighbors.name: Ethington & Hwy 84 LLC
neighbors.claims: Ethington & Hwy 84, LLC is an Arizona limited liability company formed in March 2022 ([ecorp.azcc.gov](https://ecorp.azcc.gov/BusinessSearch/BusinessInfo?entityNumber=23358315#:~:text=Formation%20Date%3A)). It is a joint venture between local real estate developers and investors: Willis Holdings, L.C. and Elche Investments, LLC (managed by land brokers C. Dale Willis Jr. and Ryan Willis of Mesa) and two other partners ([ecorp.azcc.gov](https://ecorp.azcc.gov/BusinessSearch/BusinessInfo?entityNumber=23358315#:~:text=Member%20and%20Manager%20%20,PO%20Box%202139%2C%20CHANDLER)). Additional members include TCP Investment, Inc. (an Illinois corporation represented by Michael Chen of Paradise Valley) and Hamstra Investments, LLLP (led by Carrie Hamstra of Chandler) ([ecorp.azcc.gov](https://ecorp.azcc.gov/BusinessSearch/BusinessInfo?entityNumber=23358315#:~:text=Member%20and%20Manager%20%20,4%2F7%2F2022)). The Willis family’s firm (Willis Property Co.) specializes in land deals, suggesting this LLC intends to entitle or market the Highway 84/Ethington Rd parcel for commercial or industrial development ([www.willislandco.com](https://www.willislandco.com/our-team.html#:~:text=Our%20Team%20,6200%20Office%20%5Bemail%20protected%5D)). The group has already listed the property for sale as a large industrial tract, indicating a pro-development stance and readiness to transact once a suitable project or buyer is found (no indication of opposition to new development in the area).
neighbors.influence_justification: Backed by a known land brokerage (Willis Land Co.) and capitalized by multiple investors; likely capable of lobbying for entitlements or legal action, though not a grassroots force

approach_recommendations.engage: Engage the Willis family (managing members) directly to explore collaboration or a buy-out; align infrastructure planning to complement their development plans and mitigate any competitive concerns

neighbors.name: Pinal County
neighbors.claims: Pinal County (the county government) holds title to a parcel in the vicinity, likely acquired for public use (e.g. road right-of-way or tax deed) as part of its infrastructure responsibilities ([pinal.novusagenda.com](https://pinal.novusagenda.com/AgendaPublic/MeetingView.aspx?MeetingID=1809&MinutesMeetingID=-1&doctype=Agenda#:~:text=,Pinal%20County%20Attorney%E2%80%99s%20Office%2C%20Pinal)). The County’s Board of Supervisors controls zoning, permitting, and development approvals in this area, making it a key decision-maker for any proposed project ([pinal.novusagenda.com](https://pinal.novusagenda.com/AgendaPublic/MeetingView.aspx?MeetingID=2201&MinutesMeetingID=1326&doctype=Agenda#:~:text=PINAL%20COUNTY%20BOARD%20OF%20SUPERVISORS,Consideration%2FApproval%2FDisapproval%20of%20the%20following)). In recent years, Pinal County has actively courted and managed rapid growth – its once rural profile is shifting with the rise of industrial developments and housing expansions ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/newsletters/axios-phoenix-f78c3e70-cddb-11ef-874a-7d2e103cf713#:~:text=developments%20in%20Arizona%2C%20particularly%20population,as%20industrial%20development%20and%20affordable)). County officials generally favor projects that promise job creation and an expanded tax base, but they will scrutinize impacts on roads, water, and community standards (their stance is supportive yet conditioned on meeting regulatory requirements and public interest).
neighbors.influence_justification: Local governing authority with power to approve or deny projects; can mobilize public resources and political support; direct say in land use and infrastructure

approach_recommendations.engage: Work closely with the District Supervisor and county planning staff from the outset; highlight the project’s benefits to the local economy and address any compliance or infrastructure issues proactively to secure county support

neighbors.name: Arizona Public Service Company (APS)
neighbors.claims: Arizona Public Service (APS) is the largest electric utility in Arizona, serving a wide region including Pinal County ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pinnacle_West_Capital#:~:text=Pinnacle%20West%20Capital%20Corporation%20is,ACC)). APS owns this parcel for electric infrastructure (likely a substation or transmission corridor), integral to the regional power grid. The utility is planning major transmission upgrades and a new substation in the Casa Grande/Pinal area to meet rising power demand from growth and new industries ([www.aps.com](https://www.aps.com/en/About/Construction-and-Power-Line-Siting/Power-Line-Siting/Power-Line-Siting-Projects/Bianco-230kV#:~:text=Why%20this%20project%20is%20needed%3A)) ([www.aps.com](https://www.aps.com/en/About/Construction-and-Power-Line-Siting/Power-Line-Siting/Power-Line-Siting-Projects/Bianco-230kV#:~:text=to%20determine%20appropriate%20routes%20for,new%20lines%20to%20best%20meet)). APS generally supports development that increases electricity usage, but will prioritize grid reliability and safety – they may require the project to adhere to clearance, access, or capacity considerations. While not an opponent in the traditional sense, APS holds significant influence through regulatory channels and will assert its interests if a project affects its facilities or future plans.
neighbors.influence_justification: Dominant regional utility with substantial economic and political clout; critical to infrastructure (can support or complicate projects via grid access and power supply)

approach_recommendations.engage: Consult APS early regarding power needs or interconnection; demonstrate how the project aligns with their grid expansion plans and address any technical requirements to gain their cooperation
